    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26.15-16_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="authorial"><hi rend="underline">1.</hi></fw>           
                <fw type="curatorial">15</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        16 West Ave.
                        Cheadle
                        Cheshire
                        England
                        23rd Jan. 1958
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Professor Neihardt</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>My name is Clifford Harding, I am 21 years of age, and I live at Cheadle, in the county of Cheshire, England.</p>
                
                <p>I am writing to you now to compliment you on your amazing book. "Eagle Voice"</p>
                
                <p>As my greatest interest is the study of the North American Indian, particularly the Dakotas, this book is an invaluable aid. Never before have I read such a book on these people that portrays such a true picture of them.</p>
                
                <p>I have read other books on them such us "Fighting Indian Warriors" by <hi rend="caps">E.A.</hi> <unclear>Brininstool</unclear> "Famous Fighting Indians" by David <hi rend="caps">C.</hi> Cooke. "The Sky was their Roof" by Robin <hi rend="caps">A</hi> Kelly. The Book of American Indians" by Ralph <hi rend="caps">B</hi> Raphael. "The Book of Indian Crafts and <unclear>Lore</unclear>". by <hi rend="caps">W.</hi> Ben Hunt. and "the Last Frontier" by Howard Fast. The latter being the pitiful of the three hundred "Cheyennes" march from the Oklahoma reservation back to the Black Hills under the leadership of "Little Wolf" and.

                <fw type="authorial"><hi rend="underline">2.</hi></fw>               
                <fw type="curatorial">16</fw>
                
                    Dull Knife. in the year 1878.</p>
                
                <p>I have also seen many films about them. In my opinion the films nearest the true facts were "Battle of <unclear>Powder</unclear> River". "Valley of Fury" and "White Feather". the others although very well filmed are apt to be rather like an "Ohunku Kupi"</p>
                
                <p>I should like to ask a question of you about <add>the</add> latter film which was the story of the removal of the Cheyennes. from their beloved country to the Indian reservation further South. In the film the name of the Chief was Broken Hand. was this name true.</p>
                
                <p>Through the pages of your book I have been able to learn a little of the language of the Dakota, but I would like to know the meaning of the names of such bands as Oglala, Minniconjou, Brule, San <unclear>Ural</unclear>, <unclear>Wunblee</unclear>, Sisseton, and Hunkpapa. Also <add>the</add> three main tribal nations Santee, Leton, an<del/><add>d</add> <unclear>Yangton</unclear>.</p>
                
                <p>I am attemptin<del/><add>g</add> to write a peom<sic>poem</sic> about the Dakotas from the time of the early settlers to the death of Sitting Bull in 1890. in the same style as those about "Hiawatha" by <hi rend="caps">H.W.</hi> Longfellow.</p>
                
                <p>I would like to one day to visit America and to me<del/><add>e</add>t you and to visit one of the Indian reservations.</p>
                
            </div1>
